\par
\b Q: What is the difference between oper flag P and p?\b0\par
A: To be honest, NONE except that they both can be given different on-join-modes.\par
   To give a on-join-mode for P use\par
     X:HIGHPROT:[Q|O|V|NORM]\par
   To give a on-join-mode for p use\par
     X:LOWPROT:[Q|O|V|NORM]\par
\par
\b Q: Where's ChanServ/NickServ/MemoServ?\b0\par
A: Other IRCX servers (IRCXpro) include the services inside the server. This is a bad, bandwidth-wasting\par
   idea. ignitionServer, however, handles services like any other self-respecting IRC server should. You\par
   connect services as a link, and services does the job it needs to do. You need an IRC services that is\par
   compatible with standard RFC 1459 IRC (Anope works really good, I hear). You may also need to tweak\par
   some IRC server specific settings (i.e. you probably don't want to use Unreal's SVSMODE). If you want\par
   services specifically designed for Windows and ignitionServer, use ignitionServices. More information\par
   can be found at our website.\par
\par
\b Q: What's the difference between IRCD and IRCX?\b0\par
A: Simply put, nothing. There's a common misconception about these acronyms. An IRCX server is just as\par
   much an IRCD as any other type of IRC server. If you think that an IRCD is something that's not IRCX,\par
   I probably just confused the hell out of you. IRCD means "IRC server" (daemon is a word used by UNIX\par
   and UNIX-like systems [Linux] to mean "server"). IRCX means "Internet Relay Chat eXtensions". When\par
   IRCX is properly implemented, it is RFC 1459 (the IRC specification) plus the IRCX draft. IRCX is not\par
   a protocol, but an extension to a protocol. In theory, any regular RFC 1459-compliant server can add\par
   these extensions. Many people think that IRCDs have weird modes and are "not IRCX". However, you could\par
   easily turn something like UnrealIRCD into an IRCX server, because IRCX only defines additions to the\par
   IRC protocol.\par
\par
   In most circumstances, the differences between regular IRC, and IRC with the extensions (IRCX) are as\par
   follows. First off, IRCX adds several security-oriented commands, like ACCESS (get/set/unset who has\par
   access to what levels in a channel) and AUTH (show proof you have credentials to access the server).\par
   IRCX also adds another level of channel users, the owner. In RFC 1459, only hosts (@) and voices (+)\par
   were defined. Since RFC 1459's conception in the 80's, IRC servers have added many extra levels, so\par
   this is somewhat irrelevant. However, in true IRCX (which is RFC 1459 + extensions), there are only 3\par
   levels: Owner (.), Host (@), and Voice (+). Well, that, and normal user, which has no prefix. You could,\par
   in theory, have more levels than this, but you may break some really crappy clients. IRCX also provides\par
   a mechanism for sending a message to a person WITHIN a channel. Before IRCX, any message you sent to a\par
   user was sent to them directly, out of any context of a channel. In IRCX, you can use the WHISPER\par
   command, and the message will only apply to that user within that channel.\par
\par
   IRCX also has channel metadata, or "properties", which set various channel settings, like the language,\par
   the password required to be an owner, etc. Standard RFC 1459 IRC only has one key, and it's the key\par
   for getting into a locked room. The IRCX specification also calls for DATA/REQUEST/REPLY, which are\par
   very powerful commands. They are hardly used, but their applications are nearly limitless. You could use\par
   these commands for games, telling a special client to change the avatar displayed, and more. Microsoft\par
   Comic Chat uses these commands for displaying expressions of the comic characters, telling other users\par
   what character you're using, and a lot more. IRC is more flat, and is designed for text-based communication.\par
   IRCX allows a bit more dynamic conversation, and that's why some people prefer it. However, some people\par
   like IRC better because oftentimes IRC servers are a lot more powerful and have more modes and features.\par
\par
\b Q: How do I reload a modified MOTD?\b0\par
A: As an operator (with rehash privledges), type /rehash -MOTD. This will reload the Message of the Day.\par
\par
\b Q: How do I edit the Message of the Day?\par
\b0 A: In the same folder as ignitionServer, there is a file called "ircx.motd". Open this file with Notepad and\par
   save it. If the server is currently running, you will need to type /rehash -MOTD (see above).\par
\par
\b Q: How does the Auto VHost (X:AUTOVHOST) system work?\b0\par
A: The Auto VHost system is very simple to use and set up. Basically, it changes the hostname of IRC operators\par
   to a specific Virtual Host (VHost) when they log in. For this to work, there has to be an O: line and a V: line,\par
   both with the same credentials (password/username/hostmask). The X:AUTOVHOST line also needs to be set to "1"\par
   (enabled). Once these things are completed, operators can log in (with /oper), and they'll automatically get\par
   their VHost if they have one. If an operator doesn't have a VHost, it will be the same as if X:AUTOVHOST is off (0).\par
\par
\b Q: How come I'm getting this error: Error Opening File for Writing: "C:\\Program Files\\ignitionServer\\ignitionServer.exe"?\b0\par
A: You are attempting to update or uninstall ignitionServer while ignitionServer is running. This cannot be done.\par
   To exit ignitionServer, hit Ctrl-Alt-Del, and the ignitionServer.exe process (or the task, on Win9x).\par
\par
\b Q: How come I'm getting this error: Error Opening File for Writing: "C:\\Program Files\\ignitionServer\\monitor.exe"?\b0\par
A: You are attempting to update or uninstall ignitionServer while the monitor is running. This cannot be done.\par
   To exit the monitor, bring it up (from the system tray or taskbar), and press the close button in the corner.\par
\par
\b Q: Why don't my L: lines work anymore?\b0\par
A: In 0.3.5, we reverted back to C: and N: lines for compatibility reasons. Please read ircx.conf for instructions on how to\par
   use C: and N: lines (they're nearly exactly the same). Sorry for any inconvenience.\par
\par
\b Q: What is X:CREATEMODE and how do I use it?\b0\par
A: X:CREATEMODE is a new X: line that we added to give server administrators greater control over their server. It allows\par
   the administrator to choose what group of users is able to create channels. In most cases, you will just want the default\par
   of 0, which allows all users to create channels. If you are setting up a premium chat service, or otherwise will only have\par
   a fixed set of channels, you will probably want to use 1, which will only allow IRC operators to create channels. In addition\par
   to this, you can force users to register and identify to NickServ before they can create channels. To do this, set X:CREATEMODE to\par
   2. For more information, please read ircx.conf in your favorite text editor.\par
\par
